# 1) Pay, 2) Team and year, 3) win percentage
list1 = []
list2 = []
list3 = []
list4 = []
list5 = []

unmatched = []
wins_list = []



# Doing the win percentage calculation
for i in range(len(paywins_table['W'])):   
        wins_list.append((paywins_table['W'][i] / paywins_table['G'][i]) * 100)
    

k = 0
i = 0
for p in team_salaries['team-year']:
#     print(team_salaries['team-year'])
    
    if p in paylist:
       
        
        list1.append(team_salaries['total_payroll'][i])
        
        list2.insert(i, p)
        list3.insert(i, wins_list[i])
        list4.insert(i, paywins_table['yearID'][i])
        list5.insert(i, paywins_table['teamID'][i])
        i = i + 1
    
    else:
        unmatched.insert(k, p)
        k = k+1
   
        
        
        

new_table = pd.DataFrame(list1, columns = ["total_payroll"])

What can you say about the Oakland A's spending efficiency across these time periods (labeling points in the scatterplot can help interpretation). - It seems that the NYA had a low win rate but a high payroll, and later on had the highest win rate and highest payroll. It looks like this team invested in players that can be trusted to help bring in more wins - In earlier time periods it did not look like there was any correlation between payroll and win rate, but as the years went by there seemed to be more and more of a correlation. - Oakland's was interesting because of how much it moved around. In the earlier times they had higher pay rates and higher win rates. Later, between 2000 and 2014 they have a low payroll but very high win rate.
